05668nam a22009375i 9780520922044DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20202023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209220447 a10.1525/97805209220442doi  a(DE-B1597)544290  a(OCoLC)1163878323  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBQ5030.F47bH37 1999eb 7aREL0170002bisacsh04a291.3/8/09522201 aHardacre, Helen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarketing the Menacing Fetus in Japan /cHelen Hardacre.  aReprint 2019 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (332 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTwentieth Century Japan: The Emergence of a World Power ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER I. Reproductive Ritualization Before Mizuko Kuyō -- tCHAPTER 2. The Practice of Mizuko Kuyō and the Changing Nature of Abortion -- tCHAPTER 3. Abortion in Contemporary Sexual Culture -- tCHAPTER 4 The Practitioners of Mizuko Kuyō -- tCHAPTER 5. Mizuko Kuyō in Four Locales -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Sectarian Patterns in Mizuko Kuyō -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tSelected Character List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHelen Hardacre provides new insights into the spiritual and cultural dimensions of abortion debates around the world in this careful examination of mizuko kuyo—a Japanese religious ritual for aborted fetuses. Popularized during the 1970s, when religious entrepreneurs published frightening accounts of fetal wrath and spirit attacks, mizuko kuyo offers ritual atonement for women who, sometimes decades previously, chose to have abortions. As she explores the complex issues that surround this practice, Hardacre takes into account the history of Japanese attitudes toward abortion, the development of abortion rituals, the marketing of religion, and the nature of power relations in intercourse, contraception, and abortion.Although abortion in Japan is accepted and legal and was commonly used as birth control in the early postwar period, entrepreneurs used images from fetal photography to mount a surprisingly successful tabloid campaign to promote mizuko kuyo. Enthusiastically adopted by some religionists as an economic strategy, it was soundly rejected by others on doctrinal, humanistic, and feminist grounds.In four field studies in different parts of the country, Helen Hardacre observed contemporary examples of mizuko kuyo as it is practiced in Buddhism, Shinto, and the new religions. She also analyzed historical texts and contemporary personal accounts of abortion by women and their male partners and conducted interviews with practitioners to explore how a commercialized ritual form like mizuko kuyo can be marketed through popular culture and manipulated by the same forces at work in the selling of any commodity. Her conclusions reflect upon the deep current of misogyny and sexism running through these rites and through feto-centric discourse in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbortionxJapanxJapan. 0aAbortionxReligious aspects. 0aAbortionzJapan. 0aFetal propitiatory ritesxBuddhism. 0aFetal propitiatory ritesxJapan. 0aFetal propitiatory riteszJapan. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  a20th century japan the emergence of a world power.  a20th century japanese cultural practices.  aaborted fetuses.  aabortion debates.  aabortion rituals.  aabortion.  aasian culture.  abirth control.  abuddhism.  acontraception.  acultural studies.  afetal photography.  afetal wrath.  afeto centric discourse